{{More footnotes|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Manno Charlemagne | image = manno 3.jpg | caption = Manno Charlemagne | birth_name = Joseph Emmanuel Charlemagne | birth_date = April 14, 1948<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bostonhaitian.com/aggregator/categories/1?page=2|title=Haitian blogs|website=Bostonhaitian.com|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]] | death_date = December 10, 2017 (aged 69) | death_place = [[Miami Beach, Florida]], U.S. | occupation = Singer, songwriter, acoustic guitarist, activist, politician}}
'''Joseph Emmanuel "Manno" Charlemagne''' (April 14, 1948<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/manno-charlemagne-haitian-troubadour-and-political-activist-dies-at-69/2018/01/23/9dc57b52-0062-11e8-8acf-ad2991367d9d_story.html|title=‘Manno’ Charlemagne, Haitian troubadour and political activist, dies at 69|first=Phil|last=Davison|date=23 January 2018|accessdate=24 January 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> – December 10, 2017)<ref name="washingtonpost">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/manno-charlemagne-haitian-troubadour-and-political-activist-dies-at-69/2018/01/23/9dc57b52-0062-11e8-8acf-ad2991367d9d_story.html|title=‘Manno’ Charlemagne, Haitian troubadour and political activist, dies at 69|first=Phil|last=Davison|date=January 23, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 24, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180124061001/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/manno-charlemagne-haitian-troubadour-and-political-activist-dies-at-69/2018/01/23/9dc57b52-0062-11e8-8acf-ad2991367d9d_story.html|archive-date=2018-01-24|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> was a [[Haiti]]an political [[folk singer]], songwriter and acoustic guitarist, political activist and [[politician]]. He recorded his political [[chanson]]s in both French and in Creole. He lived abroad in exile twice, both during the 1980s and again during the years 1991–1994, when the country was ruled by a military ''[[military junta|junta]]'' led by [[Raoul Cédras]].
==Early life== Charlemagne grew up in [[Carrefour, Haiti|Carrefour]], to the south of the capital of [[Port-au-Prince]], where he was influenced as much by the songs of the peasants who moved into the area in search of a livelihood, as by his Catholic school choir. Raised by his aunt, he did not know who is father was until he was 37 years old.<ref name=":0"/>
==Political career== In 1986, after the fall of the Duvalier dictatorship, Charlemagne organized a youth group and choir in his old neighborhood, Carrefour. For a brief time following [[Bertrand Aristide]]'s landslide victory on 16 December 1990, Charlemagne found himself in the role of a government booster. He served as an unofficial minister in the Aristide cabinet, an assignment that ended abruptly nine months later, when a military junta overthrew Haiti's first freely elected president.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.haitianbeatz.com/board/threads/singer-manno-charlemagne-undergoes-difficult-brain-cancer-operation-in-miami.15161 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-12-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010719/http://www.haitianbeatz.com/board/threads/singer-manno-charlemagne-undergoes-difficult-brain-cancer-operation-in-miami.15161/ |archive-date=2017-12-13 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
On 11 October, a truckload of troops pulled up to his home, roughed him up in front of his family, and hauled him off to jail. His wife, Chantel, went into hiding with the couple's baby son, Ti-Manno, and later fled to the island of [[Guadeloupe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/content/printVersion/233748|title=Manno Charlemagne|date=January 29, 1992|author=Steven Almond|work=[[Miami New Times]]|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>
==Music== Charlemagne took up guitar and singing at the age of 16. By 1968, he had formed a band named ''Les Remarquables.'' He later started a twoubadou band named ''Les Trouvères'' with Marco Jeanty.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwEL9mUcVA8C&pg=PA274&dq=toto+necessite&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjY2suoxuLRAhVHKiYKHSNMBXYQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=toto%20necessite&f=false|title=A Day for the Hunter, a Day for the Prey: Popular Music and Power in Haiti|last=Averill|first=Gage|date=April 15, 2008|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226032931}}</ref>
==Death== Charlemagne died in [[Miami Beach, Florida]] on December 10, 2017, aged 69, after a struggle of several months with lung cancer which had spread to his brain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/obituaries/article189067264.html|title=Haitian folk singer who had sharp words for politicians dies in Miami Beach|author=Glenn Garvin|publisher=Miami Herald|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref>
==Discography== 1978, ''Manno et Marco'', Marc Records
